caption: This is the best place in town! The piña coladas are incredible and the customer service is outstanding ❤️ Oscar and José at rooftop are fantastic and Alayna downstairs is great. I love this place.

Amazing spot. Been going for a couple years now. Food and drink are amazing of course, but best of all is the service. Just recently ordered a large "celebration pack" for weekend pickup. When I got there, there was an unfortunate mixup with someone with the same name as me who canceled their order and mine had been accidentally cancelled instead. The staff were extremely apologetic and were able to get my whole order together (a LOT of food) in 20 minutes. They added many other items to make up for the mistake and I honestly couldn't be more impressed with their generosity and overall customer service!

I can’t say enough about their catering.  We are Cubans from Miami and wanted to host a Cuban-themed party (with our DC-Cubans).  Daniella Senior worked with us for the catering. So I love the cuban sandwich here, but it's been the only thing I've liked. Guava pastelito was dull and flavorless, the pastry dough itself was tough. The biggest disappointment was the coffee! I ordered the drink with condensed milk and selected "miami sweet", expecting something along the lines of Vietnamese coffee (also made with strong coffee and condensed milk), what I got was literally milk with a shot of espresso. I honestly thought it was the wrong drink until I asked. What a waste of $8 (yes that's right, $8!!!) on what was basically a glass of milk, not even condensed milk!

This review is for the new Wharf location.  I was thrilled to learn that the Colada Shop was opening a new location at the Wharf. I was a casual customer when I lived in U Street, and was excited for a new affordable food spot to open in the sparse Wharf. I went two days after opening and was very impressed by the decor and the fact that they were willing to open in the middle of the Covid-19 crisis.  My complements end there. I ordered two cuban sandwiches and attempted to order a guava frozen (there machine was down although they had opened two days prior). In regards to service, there was a long line, but their cashiers were efficient and kind; however, the wait for the food was simply unacceptable. I waited 25 minutes for my two sandwiches and actually had to stand in line again to inquire about the status before they checked in the back and brought out my order. Waiting for my order was frightening, there did not have social distancing signs and did not enforce social distancing or mask usage in such a small space. When I got home, I was very disappointed in the flavor of the cuban sandwich, they were dry and thee bread was soggy, probably for having been sitting in the back.  Since I am a local, I may try again after the novelty has worn off and the there are not long lines. However, for right now it simply isn't worth the risk. There is no pre-order and pickup, the food is just okay, and there are crowds not adhering to Covid recommendations.
Come for the amazing coffee and food, and stay for the cocktails and rooftop! Love this place

Unbelievably poor service. Showed up at pick-up time to find a dozen people waiting on the patio. Order backlog meant complete inability to be remotely distant from others.  Employees then shouted out orders in rapid succession, meaning everyone crowded the window at once. After waiting 15 minutes from the car, we had to walk through a crowded counter to get the order.  This somehow wasn’t enough for 1 Star, but our completely butchered order was. Colada Shop messed up the amount of each drink pouch variety, the amount of each empanada variety, missed the Cuban, and missed the key lime pie. I’d think it maybe wasn’t our order due to how embarrassingly incorrect it was... but no, overall quantities of drinks and empanadas were correct and our name was on the bag.  Don’t go here, they don’t care about doing the absolute minimum to ensure you get your order accurate and safe.

The Cuban coffees are rich and delicious, and they do have seasonal lattes and other inspired drinks. $6 cocktails at happy hour (and $2 empanadas, also very good if you want a quick, savory bit) are amazing, considering how high quality they are. (Hemingway daiquiri & Carajillo pictured)  I highly recommend Colada Shop if you're looking for unique flavors to brighten up your day!

The Colada Shop is as authentic as Cuba Libre. I was excited to try out this cute Cuban-inspired cafe featuring cool cocktails and hearty sandwiches, but was underwhelmed by the poor quality of the food and grumpy service.  The vibrant photos of the food featured on the website and posters inside the shop couldn't be more misleading. The snacks looked sad and droopy sitting in the glass display and buried inside drawers that the staff pulled out to deep fry. It was appalling to watch as I was reminded of when Dunkin Donuts pulls out patties for their breakfast sandwiches. Those empanadas and balls didn't look fresh! I'm glad I ate beforehand. The service was really standoffish and as unwelcoming as the food. No one cracked a smile and didn't hear please or thank you once.  I wasn't a big fan of the tangy Babalu passionfruit and rum cocktail with poppyseeds sprinkled on top. The best part about the shop was tucked away in the back with comfy sofas and vibrant high chairs that made you forget that you were in DC and escaped to Cuba.  If I'm in the area, I would consider giving the shop a 2nd chance to try the signature Pina Colada. But with Jubilee right next door, I love my dessert!

A bit pricey for the portions, but what else is new in DC. All the empanadas are soooo good! Likely gonna be back.

I also got the churros which were amazing, but it does take a wait to make them. The rooftop is so beautiful so that definitely added to my experience. nice selection of craft cocktails and very tasty empanadas. happy hour you get $2 off cocktails and empanadas are only $2. Great price for a quick stop after leaving the office. Nice patio and open air seating with music playing.

A sad excuse of a Cuban eatery. This restaurant wannabe does not remotely do justice to our culinary repertoire. The owner needs to go to Miami and learn a little from real Cuban restaurants.

Cute vibe. Got caught in the rain and this offered the perfect spot to wait it out. This cuban spot is perfect for a small plate of food and very good and interesting drinks. I had the babalu which had this wonderful warm flavor. It was great I highly recommend it. Also tried the banana leaf chips. Very good! Thursday nights is Havana nights with $2 empanadas and $6 cocktails. Really good but I probably wouldn't see me drinking more than one or two drinks here. If the goal is to get a good buzz going and call it a night with out getting I a crowded space this might be your spot!

Ambiance was nice. It was very crowded. I dont like Cuban food generally so I only had the guava pastry but my friends ate more food than I did and enjoyed it. The nightclub attached to it was very nice.
Amazing Cuban sandwiches! However very hard to find a seat and gets really crowded on the weekends. Guess that shows how delicious their food/drinks are!
Food was so good! The drinks were strong & the rooftop is an experience you don't wanna miss!

Asked for a plastic cup because I was with my handsy one year old and noted I was afraid he'd break it at the low table and hurt himself. The young lady said "that's not how we make them." Seemingly an issue with intention to leave with an alcoholic drink. Legally not their issue of course. She assured me that they had a first aid kit on site? Seems a great representation of the service.
Absolutely love their churros
Best pina colada ever!
Great cuban coffee. The place is great. So great that is always full.

I'm glad I finally got a chance to try this place! It's a small spot, so I would avoid it during rush times, but for a weekday evening bite, it was a great choice. Most of their options are more snacks than actual meals, but they are really affordable, so you can order enough to fill you up. The food was tasty. We had different kinds of empanadas and churros and it was all good - hot, crispy, and flavorful. We also enjoyed the drinks. They weren't as strong as I prefer, but they were also affordable enough to grab a couple and they tasted great. The one downfall of this place is the wait time. I guess they cook everything to order and can't do many orders at a time, so we had to wait forever for our food, which was unexpected, given the format of the place. Like over twenty minutes for a couple of orders of empanadas and churros. And they do have those little restaurant buzzers, so it would have been fine if we could have gotten one, gone to sit down and had a drink while we waited. But for some reason, the cashier wouldn't give us one, so we had to stand at the counter the whole time, waiting for them to call our order. It was so annoying and really tarnished what would have been an otherwise perfect visit. But besides that, it was a good time. I'd definitely come back, this time armed with a hefty dose of patience. And a buzzer! 😂
The empanadas are delicious the staff is really friendly and the music is great
This place reminds me of a Miami cafe. The drinks were great, the service was fast. Had a great time.

Restaurant with a fun atmosphere, lots of outdoor seating, good prices, and quick eating. Food is Cuban themed and operates with a walk-up counter service. Food was okay, but don't go for sit-down restaurant quality meals. Great for the price. Fun restaurant and bar for any time of day.
Little gem! Absolutely loved the cuban sandwich. Great food, great cocktails and a lovely place to take a break, especially when you can get a good spot at the indoor/outdoor bar.

Do you think they'll sell me a bottle?

Great place. Relaxed. Open all day. Great for coffee and breakfast. A lunch sandwich. Or even a cocktail in the evening.
Very cute little shop with food, coffee and drinks. They have the regular cafe seating, a downstairs and a rooftop in the summer.

Good coffee and pastries. Nice spot for relaxing and people watching.

This place has really good coffee and it's the price worth it. Is really nice place but, when we went there it was really full with people. I think that most of the food is overpriced. I mean, $10 for a sandwich, that's a lot to me. They sell Pasteles de guayaba which was really good, but so expensive for a little piece. We got the 3 for $5.50 and is like a big pastel cut in 3 pieces. The restrooms are unisex and there is only 2. I had to stand in line and wait for using it. I didn't liked that that all. But that's my opinion. I think we would come back but only for coffee.

This place has the best coffee by far! The beans have a chocolatey aroma and taste and they have a good selection of pastries. There is outdoor seating towards the front that is perfect for socializing (my favorite) and indoor seating in the back that is good for reading, chilling, or studying. I have seen that they have happy hour and drinks, but I tend to stick to a late morning coffee and light snack. The Cuban ambiance and coffee quality make it the best coffee on 14th - that said I cannot speak to the evening cocktail vibe.

Maybe this place is more about cocktails.  The food was okay at best.  I got a croquetta sandwich with plantain chips, churros and mango iced tea.  I think the best things I had were the tea and churros.  The plantain chips were under seasoned and stale and the sandwich had an overwhelming flavor of the Swiss cheese and not much else.  The service on a Friday night was not great, perhaps understandable since they were packed but I had to go back several times to retrieve items from my order that were forgotten.
Tahira hangs out here.

I freakin loved this place! I came to visit DC for a weekend and made sure I ate here twice before I left! What’s not to love here? They have a gorgeous roof top patio where you can get croquetas and empanadas if you didn’t order enough when you were downstairs, they serve excellent vegetarian options and churros and café con leche.  If I lived in DC this would be a go to spot!  My friend and I ordered the spinach empanadas, guava cheese pastry, yucca & cheese croquetas, churros and the vegetarian ‘cuban’ sandwich. I got say I never would have thought about cauliflower for a Cuban sandwich but it works!! I wish it had more mushrooms but it was still delicious - that pressed toasted bread makes it! And you get a side of plantain chips- WIN  Oh and we can’t forget the churros con chocolate and café con leche! These didn’t disappoint either. The churros are more on the doughy type side so it’s just a matter of preference if you like crispy vs doughy. I still enjoyed them even though I tend to prefer crispier.  I also love that you can customize your café con leche “Miami sweet” or “half sweet” AND they have milk alternatives- P.S. try it with soy milk it’s very good.  Needless to say, this spot is totally worth checking out. Get a little taste of cuba/ Miami in DC  Ciao!
On a nice day you feel like you're in Cuba. Wonderful spot, all of the food is on point.  Message to the owner make the roof a patio.

F'ing love this place for breakfast! I usually hit it at least once (maaaybe twice) a week when I'm walking the dog in the morning.  The employees are lovely, and the food feels high quality for a reasonable price point. I've eaten more Starbucks factory-food microwave breakfast sandwiches than I care to count, and for a similar $5 price point you can get a much tastier, fresher breakfast sandwich at Colada Shop.  It can get a bit crazy on the weekends, but the patio is nice in good weather, and there's a maybe-almost-secret room in the back you can sometimes get a table at, even when the front area is nuts.
